<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="onboarding-flows">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>marketing</group>
    <domain>conversion-optimizer</domain>
    <summary>A design framework for guiding new users from signup to their first "Aha moment" as fast as possible. Core principle: show value before asking for work.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>onboarding</tag>
      <tag>user-activation</tag>
      <tag>saas</tag>
      <tag>funnel-optimization</tag>
      <tag>flow-design</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>onboarding</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>User Onboarding Flow Design</title>
    <summary>A design framework for guiding new users from signup to their first "Aha moment" as fast as possible. Core principle: show value before asking for work. Segment users at signup (one question), route each segment to a matching pattern (template-first / wizard / interactive / self-serve / concierge), cap the critical path at 3-5 required steps, and pair every in-app step with a triggered email that stops the moment the user activates.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Most trial churn happens before users experience value. Each additional onboarding step loses users (8 → 3 steps can raise completion from 50% to 85%). Generic flows for all segments compound drop-off because individual users get team-setup screens and evaluators get power-user prompts. Paired in-app + email sequences that stop on activation lift D0 activation rate by 20-40% vs uncoordinated email blasts.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Designing or rebuilding the first-run experience for a SaaS product where activation rate is below 50%.</item>
        <item>Choosing among onboarding patterns (template-first, wizard, interactive tutorial, self-serve, concierge) for a specific product.</item>
        <item>Reducing step count without losing necessary configuration.</item>
        <item>Adding progressive disclosure, contextual tooltips, and progress checklists to an existing flow.</item>
        <item>Coordinating in-app guidance with a triggered email sequence for the same activation goal.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>The activation event is not yet defined — pause and run activation analysis first.</item>
        <item>Pre-PMF startups where onboarding optimization masks a value-prop problem.</item>
        <item>Enterprise products with bespoke deal-by-deal onboarding — focus on Customer Success playbooks instead.</item>
        <item>Products with extremely simple value (no setup needed) — over-engineered onboarding hurts more than it helps.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="Five Onboarding Patterns">
      <rule>
        <statement>Select one onboarding pattern per user segment based on product surface and user intent; never apply the same pattern to all segments.</statement>
        <rationale>Generic patterns for all segments compound drop-off — individual users get team setup screens, evaluators get power-user prompts.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Template-first: start with pre-built example, let users customize. Best for configurable workflow tools (Notion, Trello, Canva). Fastest path to Aha for new users with no prior context.</item>
        <item>Wizard onboarding: step-by-step guided setup with 2-4 personalization questions. Best for products requiring integration/configuration (Slack, Asana, Zapier).</item>
        <item>Interactive tutorial: learn by doing inside a sandboxed demo environment. Best for spatial UIs or complex interactions (Figma, Duolingo). Requires engineering investment.</item>
        <item>Self-serve exploration: minimal guidance with optional help. Best for simple, intuitive products (Instagram, Pinterest). Avoid for products with configurable state.</item>
        <item>Concierge onboarding: high-touch 1:1 setup call. Best for enterprise B2B or products with high switching cost. Does not scale; gates growth on CS headcount.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Segmentation at Signup">
      <rule>
        <statement>Ask exactly one segmentation question at signup to route users to per-segment onboarding flows. Choices should map directly to product use cases, not demographic personas.</statement>
        <rationale>A single routing question + segment-specific flow outperforms perfectly generic flow. More than one routing question increases drop-off.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <note>One question, three routes mapping to different onboarding patterns.</note>
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[What brings you here?
[ ] Personal use       → Quick-start template flow
[ ] Team collaboration → Team setup wizard
[ ] Just exploring     → Interactive demo]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Critical Path">
      <rule>
        <statement>Define the critical path as the minimum steps required to reach the activation event — typically 3-5 steps. Everything else is optional and triggered contextually after activation.</statement>
        <rationale>Every additional required step loses users. Moving optional steps (profile photo, preferences, integrations) to contextual triggers preserves path completion without losing feature depth.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <note>Activation event: "created 1 project with 3+ tasks". Critical path has 3 required steps.</note>
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[REQUIRED (critical path):
1. Email signup
2. Create first project (with sample task pre-loaded)
3. Add 2 more tasks → activates

OPTIONAL (contextual triggers post-activation):
- Profile photo (trigger: first share action)
- Timezone preference (trigger: first calendar integration)
- Team invite (trigger: user creates 5th task)]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Optimization Tactics">
      <rule>
        <statement>Pre-fill all inferable defaults (timezone, language, plan tier) and stop asking for information the product can detect or defer.</statement>
        <rationale>Every required field that can be auto-detected or collected later reduces drop-off without data loss.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Show a progress checklist with 3-7 items and a completion percentage. Celebrate each completion. Never show an empty product state without a concrete single primary action.</statement>
        <rationale>Progress indicators increase checklist completion rate by 15%. Empty states with no action ("create your first project" with no template) force users to think before they have context.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Email Sequence Rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Kill the triggered email sequence the moment the user fires the activation event. No exceptions. Every campaign must subscribe to the activation event and exit immediately on fire.</statement>
        <rationale>Email sequences that fire after activation produce embarrassing "still need help?" messages to already-engaged users, which damages trust and increases unsubscribes.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Structure the email sequence as: Email 1 (immediate) = welcome + one action; Email 2 (Day 1) = quick-win tutorial; Email 3 (Day 3) = feature highlight; Email 4 (Day 7) = success story. Stop sending when the user activates.</statement>
        <rationale>Mid-trial check-in on day 7 of a 14-day trial outperforms higher-frequency early emails; users need quiet space to explore before being nudged.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Microcopy Rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Cap all tooltip and in-app guidance copy at 80 characters. Use neutral/direct voice — no exclamations, no emojis, no "Welcome aboard!" filler.</statement>
        <rationale>Appcues and Pendo enforce character limits. Exclamatory copy trends toward corporate-speak that users dismiss without reading.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Limit tooltip tours to a maximum of 5 items in a single session. More than 8 tooltips trigger dismiss-and-forget behavior.</statement>
        <rationale>Users stop reading tooltip sequences above ~5; every additional tooltip reduces completion of all subsequent tooltips.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Step Gating Rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Never gate the activation event behind profile completion, payment info, or optional preferences. Make those steps available but not required before the user reaches first value.</statement>
        <rationale>Required profile completion blocks the activation event and tanks Day-0 retention — the single strongest predictor of eventual conversion.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Run a no-onboarding control cell (5% of new signups) to measure the true incremental lift of the onboarding flow. Check this quarterly.</statement>
        <rationale>Onboarding sometimes adds zero net activation lift; the answer can only be found by measuring against no-onboarding. Teams that skip this sometimes discover they are adding friction, not removing it.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Tooltip tour with 8+ stops shown in the first session.</description>
        <reason>Users dismiss the entire sequence after the third tooltip; critical guidance for later steps is never seen.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>A/B testing onboarding without segmenting by user type.</description>
        <reason>Segment X gains and segment Y losses cancel out; the test appears flat even when one group benefits significantly.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Empty state with multiple "create / import / use template" calls to action of equal weight.</description>
        <reason>Users who face a choice with no hierarchy think instead of act. One primary action + two secondary fallbacks is the correct pattern.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Where It Fails / Limitations">
      <list>
        <item>Generic onboarding for all segments — individual users get team setup screens, evaluators get power-user prompts. Drop-off compounds.</item>
        <item>Tooltip tour overload: 8+ tooltips create dismiss-and-forget behavior; users miss everything.</item>
        <item>Required profile completion blocks the activation event and tanks Day-0 retention.</item>
        <item>Empty states with no concrete action ("create your first project" with no template) make the user think before they have context.</item>
        <item>Email sequences that fire after activation has occurred (no listener for the activation event) produce embarrassing "still need help?" messages to active users.</item>
        <item>A/B testing onboarding without segmentation conflates wins from segment X with losses from segment Y.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Agentic Workflow">
      <p>A Claude subagent can: (1) interview the team to extract user-segment intents and propose onboarding patterns per segment; (2) draft the critical-path step list with each step's required vs optional status; (3) write microcopy for tooltips, empty states, and progress checklists; (4) draft the triggered email sequence keyed to the same activation event; (5) read funnel drop-off data and propose 3 A/B tests per critical step. The agent should NOT auto-publish copy to production CMS — operator approves each microcopy string.</p>
      <p>Recommended subagents: faion-growth-agent (sonnet for flow design and microcopy; opus for cross-segment strategy and pattern selection). A microcopy-agent (haiku for tooltip / empty state / button label generation under tight character limits). faion-content-marketer (for the email sequence accompanying the in-app flow). faion-sdd-executor-agent (model the onboarding redesign as an SDD spec with measurable activation targets).</p>
    </section>
    <section name="CLI Tools and Services">
      <list>
        <item>posthog-cli — Query funnel + drop-off per step</item>
        <item>growthbook — Run flow A/B tests with feature flags</item>
        <item>dbt — Define activation event + funnel models</item>
        <item>playwright / cypress — Snapshot the new flow for visual review</item>
        <item>figma-cli — Pull mocks of onboarding screens for context</item>
        <item>Appcues, Pendo, Userflow, Userpilot, Chameleon, Whatfix — No-code onboarding platforms with APIs</item>
        <item>Customer.io, Loops, Intercom — Behavioral email sequences for activation</item>
        <item>Trayce / Frigade — Headless onboarding components</item>
        <item>FullStory / Hotjar, Maze — Session recording and unmoderated testing</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Best Practices">
      <list>
        <item>Define the activation event before designing the flow. Without it, optimization has no target.</item>
        <item>Cap the critical path at 3-5 steps. Move everything else behind contextual triggers ("you used X → here is how to configure it").</item>
        <item>Segment at signup with one question; route to per-segment flows. Generic flow + 1 question outperforms perfectly generic flow.</item>
        <item>Pre-fill defaults (timezone, language, plan) wherever inferable; stop asking.</item>
        <item>Pair each in-app step with a matching email — but kill the email when the user activates. No exceptions.</item>
        <item>Run a no-onboarding control cell (5%) to measure what onboarding actually adds; the answer is sometimes "nothing".</item>
        <item>Watch 10+ session recordings of the new flow before declaring success; metrics hide UX disasters.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="AI-Agent Gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>Microcopy generated by LLMs trends toward exclamatory ("Welcome aboard!"). Constrain to neutral/direct in every prompt.</item>
        <item>Character limits matter — Appcues/Pendo enforce them. Always include ≤80 chars and validate post-generation.</item>
        <item>Agents miss right-to-left and i18n constraints in copy; specify locale and force translator-friendly phrasing.</item>
        <item>"Best-practice" pattern selection from training data leads to template-first recommendations everywhere; force the agent to defend pattern choice against the actual product surface.</item>
        <item>Empty-state suggestions become checklists of features ("create / import / template") regardless of context — force a single primary action with two secondary fallbacks.</item>
        <item>Triggered email sequences proposed by the agent often fire on the wrong event; require the agent to map every email to one named event from the canonical list.</item>
        <item>Privacy: session recording snippets used for ideation must be redacted (names, emails, IDs).</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/flow-spec.md" purpose="Per-segment flow specification: segment, pattern, steps, copy, completion criterion, skip eligibility."/>
      <template path="templates/validate-flow.sh" purpose="Bash validator: fails if any onboarding step lacks a mapped analytics event."/>
    </templates>
